Compiler optimization techniques can be broadly classified into two categories: static and dynamic.

For example, if a function is called multiple times in a program, the compiler can replace the function call with the body of the function, reducing the overhead of function calls and improving the execution time.
3. Dead code elimination: This technique involves removing code that is never executed from the generated machine code to reduce the size of the executable and improve the execution time. For example, if a branch in the source code is always taken in the same direction, the compiler can remove the code that is never executed, reducing the size of the executable and improving the execution time.
4. Constant folding: This technique involves replacing constant expressions with their values to reduce the number of instructions and improve the execution time.
